<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1437,1802,2045]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,470,1802,1829]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Venezuelan species, recognized by the combination of small size (ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.37" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="2.37">2.37 mm</quantity>
), the pronotum with moderately deep impressions separated by narrow reliefs, the elytra with large and deep strial punctures, interstriae and spaces between punctures narrow ridges, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1233,1317,1875,1901]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1732,1757]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,211,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1435,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 22. Hydrochus hellmani n. sp., habitus and male genitalia of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3587227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3587227/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
; described below). Completely reliable determinations will include dissection of males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1437,1802,2045]" lastBlockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1946,1973]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Description</emphasis>
. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[608,694,1947,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1732,1757]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,211,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1435,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 22. Hydrochus hellmani n. sp., habitus and male genitalia of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3587227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3587227/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Size: 
<typeStatus box="[779,877,1947,1973]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">holotype</typeStatus>
male (length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 2.37/0.92; head width 0.60; pronotum l/w 0.53/0.57; PA 0.55; PB 0.47; elytra 1.50/0.92. Body size small (ca. 
<quantity box="[200,305,2019,2045]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.37" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="2.37">2.37 mm</quantity>
). Dorsum black, with slight iridescence, elytra without black spots. Legs dark brown. Punctation on elytra large, deep, ca. 2– 
<date box="[424,450,153,179]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">3x</date>
that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae much narrower than strial puncture diameter, narrow ridges. Interstria 9 
<superScript attach="left" box="[359,372,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">th</superScript>
more convex than others, weakly overhanging 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[943,956,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">th</superScript>
interstria. Usual area of callus on 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1365,1378,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">th</superScript>
very weakly raised.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Pronotum slightly wider than long (as ca. 53/57), widest at anterior margin, narrowed at base, sides very weakly arcuate, smooth; anterior margin very weakly bisinuate; depressions moderately deep, reliefs narrow.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Elytra with spaces between strial punctures narrow ridges; apices rather sharply conjointly rounded in dorsal view, in lateral view outer margin with slight angulation.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Ventral characters: Mentum moderately coarsely and moderately densely punctate, with shallow median fovea. Submentum with two small shallow foveae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[379,462,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1732,1757]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,211,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1435,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 22. Hydrochus hellmani n. sp., habitus and male genitalia of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3587227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3587227/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) general characters: genitalia stout; paramere tips tapering and arcing slightly toward midline, extending slightly beyond distal end of aedeagus, parameres in lateral view arcuate, and wider than dorsal/ ventral views; basal piece much shorter than parameres, tapering from distal end to base, orifice sclerotized, asymmetrical; aedeagus lanceolate, lateral margins moderately widely sclerotized, greatest width at about midlength, tapering apically, with internal lumen in basal ½, gonopore apical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" box="[199,1422,657,683]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Dorsal surface: adtl subapical; pdmm widely overlapping alm, especially in distal 1/2; adbl moderately large.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" box="[199,841,693,719]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Ventral surface: avtl subbasal; pvmm approximating alm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1170,729,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,755]" box="[199,1170,729,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,729,755]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for John Leroy Hellman, who collected the only known specimen.
</paragraph>
